text:
Adding additional thoughts from <@U0107EMK8UD> and myself. <@U0107EMK8UD> add anything that I might have missed:

1. Re the first four graphs, I agree with <@U010U8HF7PY> about getting rid of quarantined (if you’d like we can think of ways to have this as part of the resource and capacity tracking data visualization, but as i understand its, there’s a team working on that already? Maybe that can be added later?) I would suggest adding number tested as another graph. 

2. Both <@U011680TZL5> and <@U010U8HF7PY> suggested a graphic representing a timeline analysis of cases. I think that’s important to add. Suggested from <@U0107EMK8UD> and I —     a scatter plot (and then line graph when enough cases build) showing on the X-axis the # of dates since first case was reported in Ethiopia—if possible in each region and # cases on y axis
. Attached an example. 

3. To <@U010U8HF7PY> what needs to be added section, in addition to cases by hospitalization status, ICU admission, and outcome, would include cases by number tested. Would make these by region. 

4. Resource/capacity need visualization 
— agree with both above. Information on hospital beds, ICU beds, ventilators, and PPE might be useful. As Mahlet mentioned, it would be worth knowing what MOH would find useful AND what they are planning  on having folks track already. This requires continues updating and if there aren’t point people or a system to periodically collect. 

5. Additional internal use graphic: Not sure if MOH is already doing this but some transmission network graphic (of Addis for now given that’s the concentration of almost all cases) might be useful for contact tracing
. I’m not expert at this at all but it looks like a tool that is used to trace the outbreak— example here: <https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.03.18.20038638v1.full.pdf|https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.03.18.20038638v1.full.pdf> (<@U010T8D05UM> - do you have any experience using this kind of tool? Are there others you might suggest that could be helpful for MOH in context of contact tracing)

text:
<@U0107DX4VNU>  I think you got everything. I am available for a call too. Here are some additional points I wanted to add                                                                             1. I think it is worth contacting MOH about how a medical service area is designated in order to map out the availability of resources. Here in CA for example, there are MSSAs. Since there are often hierarchies of medical centers in Ethiopia, this designation would provide practical information in trying to map out the capacities of hospitals and clinics. Once we have that information, we can easily figure out the unit of analysis to visualize capacity. 
2. For folks on the ground and internal use, it may be helpful to have a breakdown of preexisting conditions that cases may have. This may be helpful in monitoring those who may be at higher risk for complications and for resource allocation. Something like the image below is what i have in mind.
3. Related to the above point, if we do have the data, it may also be helpful to have the distribution of the most common symptoms that patients presented prior to getting tested. But I understand if that data is not available. 
4. To <@U010U8HF7PY> ’s point everyone is getting “quarantined” right now. Hopefully this doesn’t happen but in the case that the isolation facilities are at capacity, we may see cases being told to “self quarantine” in their homes. If that happens, I think we would need to know how many are being sent home and how many are being sent to the isolation facilities.
